'''''Samantha Fox Strip Poker ''''' is a 1986 [[erotic video game]] developed by Software Communications and published by [[Martech]]. It was published on the [[Commodore 64]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[BBC Micro]], [[MSX]], and [[ZX Spectrum]].

It is one of the first erotic video games to include a real human being. It is part of a theme of erotic games where players complete difficult tasks and are rewarded with nudity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.geek.com/samantha-fox/ |title=Samantha Fox Strip Poker - Geek.com |access-date=2018-03-24 |archive-date=2018-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325012438/https://www.geek.com/samantha-fox/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Gameplay==
The players plays 5-card or 7-card stud poker against British  model and singer [[Samantha Fox]]. Winning hands results in her taking off her clothes until she is topless.

==Development==
The video game was programmed by Wolfgang Smith, with the graphics edited by Malcolm Smith. The author of the music is [[Rob Hubbard]], credited with the name John York. The music includes a cover of "[[The Entertainer (rag)|The Entertainer]]" by [[Scott Joplin]] and "[[The Stripper]]" by [[David Rose (songwriter)|David Rose]].

==Reception==
''[[ZZap!64]]'' felt the music was well-suited to the style of game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/zzap64-magazine-016|title=ZZap!64 Magazine Issue 016|date=1 August 1986|publisher=|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> ''Commodore Format'' magazine thought that the idea of anybody using the game as a way to experience titillating content was depressing due to the required amount of effort from the player.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/commodore-format-magazine-41|title=Commodore Format Magazine Issue 41|date=1 February 1994|publisher=|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> 

Uvejuegos thought the game was a prime example of how strange the 1980s were.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uvejuegos.com/analisis/Samantha-Fox-Strip-Poker/Desnudando-a-Samantha-Fox/4656/33974|title=Análisis de Samantha Fox Strip Poker para C64 (Pag. 1) - uVeJuegos.com|first=Álvaro Morillas Correa|last=(CodeRed)|website=uvejuegos.com}}</ref> ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' placed the game within the sub-genre of early pixelated digi-ladies of dubious beauty, along with Artworx's ''[[Strip Poker (video game series)|Strip Poker]]'' (1984).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/web/gamers-corner-sex-sells-a-117867.html|title=Gamers Corner: Sex sells|date=2001-02-16|work=Spiegel Online|access-date=2018-03-24}}</ref>

